,"A mineral name that has received formal approval by the International Mineralogical Association (IMA)"],[21,"A mineral that is a type of the mineral species, distinguished by color or other optical phenomenon or characteristic"],[12,"A name assigned by an authoritative body based on a defined set of unambiguous criteria and belonging to a formal nomenclature"],[9,"A name by which a geologic material is frequently referred, without reference to any formal usage or structure nor sanctioned by an authoritative body"],[16,"A name defined in prior standards or classification systems but has since been removed from those authoritative sources. Includes names designated by the International Mineralogical Association as discredited or obsolete."],[11,"A name derived from an authoritative classification system at any rank"],[26,"A natural, solid object, derived from a celestial body, that was transported by natural means from the body on which it formed to a region outside the dominant gravitational influence of that body and that later collided with a natural or artificial body larger than itself."],[27,"A naturally occurring element or chemical compound of homogeneous composition, normally with a crystalline structure, and resulting from some geological process on Earth or in extraterrestrial bodies"],[28,"A naturally occurring geological material from which economically valuable minerals can be extracted."],[36,"A role played by a chemical compound which is known to induce a process of carcinogenesis by corrupting normal cellular pathways, leading to the acquistion of tumoral capabilities."],[39,"A sample or preparation containing inflammable, flammable or flame-sustaining materials, whether naturally, or as part of treatment or storage materials."],[35,"A sample or specimen containing acicular or fibrous asbestos (serpentine or amphibole) minerals, either naturally or as part of storage materials, which can cause internal damage if breathed or ingested."],[33,"A sedimentary structure produced by the life activities (other than growth) of some organism"],[38,"A solid or liquid chemical which is in itself capable by chemical reaction of producing gas at such a temperature and pressure and at such a speed as to cause damage to the surroundings."],[14,"An alias of a mineral name used within a historical context or derived from a historical source"],[19,"An alias of a mineral species no longer recognized as the official classification"],[40,"Any material containing unstable atoms that emit ionizing radiation as it decays."],[24,"Any mineral or naturally occurring substance that, when cut and polished, has sufficient beauty, rarity, and durability for use as a personal adornment or other ornament."],[23,"Any remains, trace, or imprint of a plant or animal preserved in the Earth's crust since some past geologic or prehistoric time; loosely, any evidence of past life."],[31,"Astromaterial returned from sample collection missions to celestial objects (e.g. comets, asteroids, the Moon, Mars)"],[29,"Consolidated aggregate of one or more EarthMaterials, or a body of undifferentiated mineral matter, or of solid organic material. Includes mineral aggregates such as granite, shale, marble; glassy matter such as obsidian; and organic material such a coal. Excludes unconsolidated materials."],[32,"Man-made materials created in a laboratory that are intended to representative of natural occurring geological material"],[17,"Name of the solid solution series to which a specimen belongs."],[10,"The name of a geological material for cataloging or presentation purposes."],[13,"The name of a mineralogical group a specimen belongs to. Groups are defined as a set of mineral species with essentially the same crystal structure and composed of chemically similar elements."],[20,"The name of a mineralogical specimen that is pending approval as an offical name by the International Mineralogical Association (IMA)"],[8,"The proportion of a material component varies significantly within the material entity or across specimens"]],"type":"string"},"scheme":{"docs":{"1":20,"2":21,"3":22,"4":23,"5":24,"6":25,"7":26,"8":27,"9":28,"10":29,"11":30,"12":31,"13":32,"14":33,"15":34,"16":35,"17":36,"18":37,"19":38,"20":39,"21":40,"22":0,"23":1,"24":2,"25":3,"26":4,"27":5,"28":6,"29":7,"30":8,"31":9,"32":10,"33":11,"34":12,"35":13,"36":14,"37":15,"38":16,"39":17,"40":18,"41":19},"orderedDocs":[[22,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[23,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[24,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[25,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[26,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[27,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[28,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[29,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[30,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[31,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[32,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[33,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[34,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/geological-specimen-type"],[35,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/hazard-type"],[36,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/hazard-type"],[37,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/hazard-type"],[38,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/hazard-type"],[39,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/hazard-type"],[40,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/hazard-type"],[41,"http://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/hazard-type"],[1,"https://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/constituent-part-proportion"],[2,"https://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/constituent-part-proportion"],[3,"https://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/constituent-part-proportion"],[4,"https://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/constituent-part-proportion"],[5,"https://vocab.geospecimens.org/def/constituent-part-proportion"